PERIODIC CHOLERA REPORT
AFRICA
Democratic Republic of the Congo:
Date: 9 June 2000
From: Craig E. Gibson
Source: Electronic Mail and Guardian [edited

More than 1000 people, most of them children, have been struck down by
cholera in the eastern DR-Congo, exacerbated by heavy flooding. A pack of
pictures taken in Kisangani shows a row of thin children with sinking eyes
lying in a cholera camp, with drips hanging above their beds to replace
lost fluids. Kisangani is the largest city in the east of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC), on the border with Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi.
"The situation is pathetic there. Everybody is scared of the cholera
epidemic," said a photographer, just back from the city. The photographer,
who was hired by a European non-governmentalorganization (ngo), told IPS
this week that the disease was claiming the lives of children more than any
other group. Confirming this, the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
office in Kisangani reported that the epidemic -- which escalated after
heavy flooding in the region in late December -- had claimed 231 lives and
struck 1235 people, the majority of whom are children.
********
Liberia
Date: 9 June 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Africa News Online [edited

Liberia's health minister, Dr Peter Coleman, Wednesday said cholera has
broken out in south-eastern Maryland County, where the disease has struck
about 150. "We have recorded three deaths at the moment," he told PANA. He
added that most of the victims are children aged between 5 and 15 years.
Coleman explained disease broke out due to unavailability of safe drinking
water in Maryland County, some 290 km from Monrovia. But he said his
ministry has already sent a medical team to the area to help contain the
disease.
********
Kenya
Date: 2 June 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: East African Standard [edited

Four people have died of cholera in Shinyalu division of Kakamega District
in the last one week, area Medical Officer of Health, Dr Quinto Ahindukha,
said yesterday. He said following the outbreak of the disease, several
other people have been hospitalized. Ahindukha said the disease had been
reported in Khayega, Shiruli and Lukose sub locations, adding that public
health officers had been rushed to the area to help curb its spread. He
said the 4 died while undergoing treatment at St Elizabeth Mission Hospital
Mukumu and the Kakamega Provincial GeneralHospital. Ahindukha said the most
affected areas were Ikhobero in Tiriki location, Shiruli, Lukose, Khwirenyi
and Lukongo in Shibuye and Khayega locations. He said since the outbreak
last week, more people may have died as the victims were immediately buried
to curb the spread of the disease. He banned eating at funerals and warned
that those found contravening the ban will be arrested. Ahindukha said his
officers had reported lack of latrines as the main cause
of the cholera outbreak. He urged chiefs and their assistants to ensure
that toilet facilities are put up immediately. He said public health
officers have been dispatched to the division to enforce the ban on hawking
and selling of cooked food at the market centers. The officers will also
supply drugs to local health centers for treatment of the disease.
[Byline: Seth Musisi
****
[2
Date: 22 May 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: African Standard Online [edited

Eight people have died of cholera in Mandera district in the last one week,
area Medical Officer of Health, Dr Peter Mbugua said yesterday. Dr Mbugua
said an average of 5 cholera patients are admitted at the hospital's
isolation ward every day following the outbreak. He said an acute shortage
of drugs and staff had hampered their efforts to combat the disease. Dr
Mbugua said more than 70 cholera patients have been treated and discharged
while 11 others in a critical condition. He however noted that most deaths
were due to starvation owing to the prevailing drought. The disease has
spread to Rhamu Division, the medic said. Dr Mbugua said cases of dysentery
and diarrhea have been reported in Dandu and Ashabito areas. The District
Public Health Officer, Mr Adan Mohammed, said financial constraints and
lack of vehicles hampered efforts to conduct health education throughout
the district.
[Byline: Osman Mohammed
****
[3
Date: 18 May 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: East African Standard Online [edited

Ministry of Health officials in Nyanza province have issued a cholera alert
as one person died of the disease in Homa Bay District. Thirteen other
people are admitted in various health centers as officials fear the spread
of the disease. Nyanza public health officer, Mr George Otieno, cautioned
residents to ensure they use safe drinking water. He said a team of health
officers has been constituted to handle emergency cases. Otieno said the
team has visited Bondo, Suba and Nyando districts to assess the situation
which he described as stable. Homa Bay public health officer, Mr Elly
Nyambok, said the victim died at the
district hospital where 4 others have been admitted. He said 5 others were
undergoing treatment at Ndhiwa health center while four more are recovering
at Nyagoro health center. Rangwe MP, Dr Shem Ochuodho, called for the
prosecution of local authorities that are discharging raw sewage into Lake
Victoria.
[Byline: Alphayo Otieno & David Ohito
********
Nigeria
Date: 23 May 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack<pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Panafrican News Agency [edited

[The death toll in the outbreak of cholera epidemic in Ilaje Local
Government Areas of Ondo State reportedly increased to 60 including one of
the soldiers recently deployed to keep peace in the crisis area. Additional
20 people were confirmed dead by the council chairman, Mr. Adebowale
Ajimuda while speaking to newsmen in Akure yesterday. Those who died,
according to him were among the 100 that were hospitalized last week.
Vanguard learnt that with the death of the soldier, his colleagues now live
in fear and have abstained from drinking from the stream. The state health
commissioner in his comment said that the epidemic was being effectively
contained adding that patients should be taken to government hospitals
instead of private clinics.
[Byline: Dayo Johnson Akure
********
Uganda
Date: 7 June 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: The Monitor [edited

Mukono district director of health services, Dr Elly Tumushabe, has
dismissed reports that there is a cholera outbreak in the district. He said
there is no way such a closely monitored disease could have taken the
district's satellite units unaware. Dr Tumushabe was responding to a report
in the May 27 issue of Bukedde, a Luganda daily, that 5 people, 2 from the
same house, died of cholera in Kanjuki village, Namukuma parish, Busaana
sub-county on May 25. He said a system surveillance officer at Kayunga
Hospital is in contact with both the
grassroots and district medical department, and he couldn't have failed to
note the incidents. He added that the multiplier effect of a cholera case
has a fast and big effect, that within a few hours, many people would have
died.
****
[2
Date: 23 May 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Africa News Network

Five people died and 76 new cases of cholera were identified in an outbreak
in displaced people's camps in Bundibugyo District, western Uganda, between
April 27 and May 9 (the latest date for which accurate figures were
available), according to an UNOCHA mission report. This brings the total
cholera cases to 303, with 22 deaths recorded, between 27 February and last
week, it said. Over 90 percent of the cholera cases occurred in Mantoraba
camp, with another nine percent in Ntandi camp, it added. Medecins sans
frontieres (MSF) - France was the only agency trying to provide health care
services to some 49 IDP camps in Bundibugyo, and was severely
overstretched, OCHA reported.
********
AMERICAS
Honduras
Date: 1 June 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack<pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Agencia EFE [edited

At least 3 people have died from cholera in Honduras's border region with
El Salvador, and seven new cases of the disease have been reported, a
Health Ministry official said Thursday. The deaths have all occurred in the
town of Yarula, in the province of La Paz bordering with El Salvador,
according to the Health Ministry's cholera control officer, Leonel Guillen.
Seven other Yarula residents have also been infected with the sickness,
adding to the 6 cases already recorded this year in other parts of
Honduras. Guillen said the incidence of cholera in Yarula constitutes an
epidemic, and measures have been established to control the spread of the
disease, introduced in Yarula by individuals who became infected in El
Salvador. El Salvador has reported hundreds of cases of cholera, prompting
Honduran authorities to set up epidemiological barriers.
********
SOUTHWEST ASIA
India
Date:1 June 2000
From: Dr. Rajesh Vaid <rajesh@cirg.up.nic.in>
Source: News media [edited

The beggars home in Narela, run by Social Welfare Dept. of Delhi govt. is
in grip of Cholera epidemic since 23 of May. Fifteen patients suffering
from gastroenteritis and Cholera have been taken to the Infectious Hospital
at the Kingsway camp for treatment. As many as 25 suspected cholera
patients and three confirmed cholera cases, are presently admitted. Medical
officials said that confirmation of the presence of _Vibrio cholera_ in
other patients who were brought to the hospital will be done tomorrow. This
is the first incidence of clustering of cholera cases reported so far this
year. The total number of cases reported this year has now crossed the
100 mark. Maximum number of cases have been reported from the central Zone-
50 and from civil lines zones-13. Three cases were reported in January, 37
in April and 90 this month (May). There has been no mortality. The number
of gastroenteritis cases reported so far this year is 18 366 which was 21
364 last year.
--
Dr. Rajesh Kumar Vaid, Scientist
Veterinary Public Health, CIRG,
Makhdoom,PO Farah 281 122 UP
India
