Iran:
Date:18 May 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack<pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: News Media [edited

A cholera outbreak in two mountain camps operated by Kurdish rebels in Iran
has killed 76 guerrillas, the Anatolia news agency said Wednesday. Another
56 rebels of the Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, have been hospitalized
since the May 2 outbreak, Anatolia reported. The report could not be
independently verified.
********
Kazakstan
Date: 17 May 2000
From: Alex Vladyko <vladyko@briem.ac.by>
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for NIS/CIS
Source: ITAR-TASS [edited

Berik Torgusov, a Chief Sanitary Physician of the South-Kazakstan province
(oblast) in Kazakstan reported that 126 carriers of the El Tor vibrio
(including 74 children) had been registered in the province. All of them
were hospitalized with diagnosis of vibriosis. The local government
allocated 1.2 million tenge (near US $8400) for the treatment. In the
province the cholera cases were registered in 1993, 1995 and 1997.
********
DIARRHEA AND DYSENTERY SECTION
Uganda:
Date: 22 May 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: New Vision (Kampala) [edited

At least 30 cases of dysentery have been reported in Nakasongola district,
following an outbreak of the epidemic on Monday. All the cases have been
reported in Kalungi and Lwampanga sub-counties, the district health
manager, Dr. Sekitto said. Sekitto said the epidemic has mostly affected
people living on the Lake Kioga shores. "We have received around thirty
cases in Lwampanga and Kalungi," Sekitto said in an interview. He said his
medical team has already visited the affected areas and stocked the health
units there with appropriate drugs. This is the second time in two years
that a dysentery epidemic is breaking up in the same area. Last year,
almost a similar number of people were affected in Lwampanga.
********
Russia:
Date: 15 June 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: ITAR/TASS News Agency [edited

As many as 174 people, among them 150 children, suffered from acute
dysentery in a children's health camp in the Ulyanovsk region. The outbreak
of the disease was caused by contaminated food served in the dining-hall.
The camp is temporarily closed.
****
[2
Date: 2 June 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: ITAR/TASS News Agency [edited

The State Sanitary and Epidemiologic Service has warned of a new cholera
outbreak in Russia. Chief sanitary doctor Gennady Onishchenko has ordered
sanitary and quarantine authorities to pay special attention to people
arriving in Russia from countries where cholera is commonplace. According
to the World Health Organization, 17 440 cholera cases were reported in the
world in the first four months of 2000. Nine hundred people died. In 1999,
there were 206 657 cholera cases in 56 countries and 6883 people died.
Outbreaks of cholera were reported last year in the Primorsky Territory and
the Sakhalin regions of Russia. They were caused by infection brought in
from China. Cholera strains were found in 17 regions of Russia.
********
South Korea
Date: 22 May 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Korea Herald [edited

Officials at the National Institute of Health said yesterday that most
epidemic diseases, such as bacillary dysentery, food poisoning, malaria,
cholera and typhoid have shown little sign of increasing this year compared
with previous years. But the NIH put health officials across the country on
special alert for highly contagious diseases out of concern that rising
temperatures may contribute to disease outbreaks. According to NIH figures,
315 people have come down with dysentery so far this year, about half the
648 reported during the same
period last year. The number of food poisoning victims also declined to 958
this year, about 33 percent of last year's 2,870. Cases of typhoid and
malaria also decreased to 65 and 56, respectively, in the first four months
of this year from 114 and 61 in the same period last year. Health
authorities are staying especially vigilant for dysentery as the disease
has been spreading in southern parts of the country since earlier this
month. It was reported yesterday that several suspected dysentery sufferers
were also discovered in Taegu and Kumi, North Kyongsang Province. This came
in the wake of reports of more than 100 possible cases in Pusan and Kochang
in South Kyongsang Province, and Kwangju and Haenam in South Cholla
Province. In Pusan, doctors have so far diagnosed 104 cases of dysentery
among some 400 elementary school students and their parents who visited a
"prayer house" in Taegu for five days from May 8. Of the confirmed
patients, 49 are in isolation for intensive treatment. Officials fear that
the number of patients may continue to increase ahead of May 24, when the
NIH is slated to complete examinations of those who participated in the
tour and about 5000 people who came in contact with them. At the moment,
the officials assume that patients contracted the epidemic from
contaminated underground water at the prayer house. Kochang also reported 2
dysentery patients and 100 others who are suffering from diarrhea, a
typical symptom of the epidemic.
********
India
Date: 2 June 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Hindustan Times [edited

The residential campus of All India Institute of Medical Sciences (AIIMS)
appears to be in the grip of typhoid with as many as 14 cases being
reported within a month. Sources in the institute said that this year the
typhoid cases appeared to be caused by a resistant type of bacteria as the
patients, some of them who are children of the faculty members, were not
responding to the usual antibiotics.
[Byline: Aruna P Sharma
****
[2
Date: 1 June 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Times of India, 1 Jun 2000 [edited

About 300 people in Yamage village of Kagal tehsil in this district have
been affected with gastroenteritis following the outbreak of water-borne
disease in the last five days here. The epidemic continues unabated with
more cases being reported at the local hospital and Chhatrapati Pramila
Raje civil hospital here. Sources said about 300 people of Yamage village
were infected due to gastroenteritis epidemic outbreak during the period
and a majority of them were being treated at local level in a specially
opened centre in the village school building. So far, nearly 20 serious
cases had been shifted to the Chhatrapati Pramila Raje civil hospital,
sources said and claimed that the disease had not claimed any life. The
epidemic was now under control, they added.
***
[3
Date: 25 May 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Rediff on the Net [edited

Doctors are describing as grim the situation arising out of a spurt in
cases of gastroenteritis and jaundice in many parts of New Delhi,
especially areas under the Trans-Yamuna and north-west Delhi. According to
Delhi Medical Association (DMA) president-elect Dr V K Monga, the picture
is grim in east Delhi. "Over 50 per cent of my out-patient department cases
are of gastroenteritis and jaundice is also on the rise," he said. The
worst-hit are Krishna Nagar, Azad Nagar, Kanti Nagar and Vishwas Nagar. The
situation in north-west Delhi is not much better. The heat wave conditions
and polluted water in Delhi led to an increase in gastroenteritis in April
and May, said Dr Naresh Chawla, practicing physician in Pritampura and DMA
vice-president. Despite increased awareness and good hygienic practices
being observed by people, this seasonal disease continues to afflict many
areas, including affluent colonies in south and central Delhi, say doctors.
Dr Monga claimed that 99 per cent reported gastroenteritis cases are
water-borne.
*******
Pakistan:
Date: 7 June 2000
From: Jack Woodall
Source: Dawn News Service - Internet Edition [edited

Officials of the Public Health Engineering Department found guilty of
negligence with respect to contaminated water of a reservoir which claimed
eight lives, will be taken to task. This was stated by Col Rana of the Army
Engineering Corps. He is assisting civil officials in the relief operation.
Col Rana told reporters on Wednesday that the analysis report of the water
had so far not been received. In the light of this report, a strict action
would be taken against responsible officials of the PHED. Meanwhile, about
100 residents affected by the contaminated water were brought to the
Bahawal Victoria Hospital, Bahawalpur on Wednesday. A dozen of them were
admitted to the hospital due to their serious condition.
